Certainly! In LaTeX, you can automatically generate a table of contents by using specific commands. Here is an example of a simple LaTeX document that includes a table of contents:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

% Include the package for advanced table of contents options (optional)
\usepackage{tocloft}

\begin{document}

% Title and author
\title{Sample Document with Table of Contents}
\author{Author Name}
\date{\today}

% Create the title
\maketitle

% Insert the table of contents
\tableofcontents

% Start the sections
\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section. Here you would typically introduce the topic of your document.

\section{Literature Review}
This section includes a review of relevant literature.

\subsection{Historical Background}
Details about the historical background of the topic.

\subsection{Recent Studies}
A summary of recent studies related to the topic.

\section{Methodology}
This section describes the methodology used in the research.

\section{Results}
This section presents the results of the research.

\section{Discussion}
This section discusses the implications of the results.

\section{Conclusion}
This section provides concluding remarks and future directions.

\end{document}
```

### Explanation of Key Commands:
1. `\documentclass{article}`: This declares the document class to be an article. You can use other document classes like `report` or `book` depending on your needs.

2. `\usepackage{tocloft}`: This package is optional and provides additional customization options for the table of contents.

3. `\maketitle`: This command generates the title, author, and date as specified by the `\title`, `\author`, and `\date` commands.

4. `\tableofcontents`: This command generates the table of contents automatically based on the sections (`\section`, `\subsection`, etc.) defined in the document.

5. `\section`, `\subsection`: These commands create sections and subsections within the document. These sections will automatically be added to the table of contents.

When you compile this LaTeX document, it will generate a table of contents that lists all the sections and subsections along with their page numbers. Note that you might need to compile the document twice to get the table of contents to display correctly, as LaTeX needs to gather information about the section headings and their page numbers in the first pass.

To draw a chessboard using FEN notation in LaTeX, we can use the `chessboard` package, which provides a simple way to display chess positions. Below is an example of how to create a LaTeX document that includes a chessboard with a given FEN notation.

First, ensure you have the `chessboard` package installed. Then, you can use the following LaTeX code:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}  % Include the chessboard package

\begin{document}

% Set the FEN notation here
\newcommand{\fen}{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}

% Draw the chessboard with the given FEN notation
\begin{center}
  \chessboard[
    setfen=\fen,
    showmover=true
  ]
\end{center}

\end{document}
```

In this code:
- `\usepackage{chessboard}` includes the `chessboard` package.
- `\fen` is a new command holding the FEN notation string.
- `\chessboard[setfen=\fen, showmover=true]` draws the chessboard using the FEN notation and indicates which side is to move.

Replace the value of `\fen` with your desired FEN string to display a different chess position. For example, to display the starting position of a chess game, you can use `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR`.

